            <fr:title text="Derived subgroup of general linear group">Derived subgroup of general linear group</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>theorem</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>We can relate the commutator subgroup of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {GL}_{n}(R)]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {SL}_{n}(R)]]></fr:tex> under certain circumstances on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex>. For skew-fields, the derived subgroup is equal to the elementary linear group.</html:p>
            <html:ol><html:li><html:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> be a unital <fr:link href="/ring-0001/" title="Ring" uri="http://localhost:8000/ring-0001/" display-uri="ring-0001" type="local">ring</fr:link> of finite stable rank <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {sr}(R)]]></fr:tex>. Then for every <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n>\mathrm {sr}(R)]]></fr:tex> we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[[\mathrm {GL}_{n}(R),\mathrm {GL}_{n}(R)]=\mathrm {EL}_{n}(R)]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>

<html:p>This follows from Vaserstein's injective stability theorem (theorem 10.15 in B. Magurn, <html:em>An Algebraic Introduction to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex>-Theory</html:em>, CUP, 2002).</html:p></html:li>

<html:li><html:p>Bass proved this is true for <html:em>any</html:em> (associative) unital ring <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> when <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\geq 3]]></fr:tex>. See <fr:link href="https://arxiv.org/abs/1510.07143" type="external">arXiv:1510.07143</fr:link>. Further when <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> is commutative, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n=1]]></fr:tex> has <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[[\mathrm {GL}_{1}(R),\mathrm {GL}_{1}(R)]=\mathrm {EL}_{1}(R)]]></fr:tex>. For more about the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n=2]]></fr:tex> case, see Cohn's "<fr:link href="/cohn-1966-structure/" title="On the structure of the \mathrm {GL}_{2} of a ring" uri="http://localhost:8000/cohn-1966-structure/" display-uri="cohn-1966-structure" type="local">On the structure of the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {GL}_{2}]]></fr:tex> of a ring</fr:link>".</html:p></html:li>

<html:li><html:p>In particular, for any field <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}]]></fr:tex>, we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[[\mathrm {GL}_{n}(\mathbb {F}),\mathrm {GL}_{n}(\mathbb {F})]=\mathrm {EL}_{n}(\mathbb {F})]]></fr:tex> when either <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\neq  2]]></fr:tex> or <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {F}\neq \mathbb {F}_{2}]]></fr:tex>.</html:p></html:li></html:ol>
